mvi-ldc-DRY-Index-eq.def: Defined as the percentage of population that lives in drylands, defined by long term averages of the ratio of precipitation to potential evapotranspiration (known as aridity index)
mvi-ldc-DRY-Index-eq.name: Share of population living in drylands
mvi-ldc-DRY-Index-eq.source: CDP Secretariat, based on an aridity index derived from high resolution climate data from University of East Anglia Climatic Research Unit (CRU TS version 4) and gridded population data from Center for International Earth Science Information Network - CIESIN - Columbia University

mvi-ldc-LECZ-Index-eq.def: Population below 5m is the percentage of the total population living in areas where the elevation is 5 meters or less.
mvi-ldc-LECZ-Index-eq.name: Share of population in low elevated coast zone
mvi-ldc-LECZ-Index-eq.source: Center for International Earth Science Information Network - CIESIN - Columbia University and CUNY Institute for Demographic Research (CIDR), City University of New York. 2020. Low Elevation Coastal Zone (LECZ) Urban-Rural Population and Land Area Estimates, Version 3 Preliminary Release. Palisades, NY: NASA Socioeconomic Data and Applications Center (SEDAC). Accessed 30 July 2020. For a number of small island and coastal States, data are from CIESIN, Population, Landscape, And Climate Estimates, Version 3 (PLACE III)

mvi-ldc-REM-Index-eq.def: Defined as a trade-weighted average of a country's distance from world markets
mvi-ldc-REM-Index-eq.name: Remoteness
mvi-ldc-REM-Index-eq.source: CDP Secretariat, based on data for exports and imports and goods and services from United Nations Statistics Division National Accounts Main Aggregates Database (AMA) and distance data from Centre d'Etudes Prospectives et d'Informations Internationales
